name: Kopitiam Bersaudara
address: Jl. Raya Sesetan No.424, Sesetan, Denpasar Selatan, Kota Denpasar, Bali, Indonesia

For a kopitiam this place is pretty okay if you just want to chill, the soft boiled eggs were cold, the kaya toast too but the taste was okay.

Milo and teh tarik was okay.

review 2: Found a hair inside the Mie Nyemek. They have two floors, with the second floor using air conditioning. When we went upstairs, the table was still messy from the previous customer.

name: Bakso MERCON Prasmanan Purwoharjo
address: Jl. Raya Sesetan No.177, Sesetan, Denpasar Selatan, Kota Denpasar, Bali 80223, Indonesia
review 1:
Best meatball stall I've ever tasted in Bali.

This stall use self services system, so you should take your own noodle, vegetables, and extra topping, while the waitress will take the meatball and its soup for you.

Various meatball available from Bakso Bom (the biggest one), bakso Mercon (spicy ones), bakso Ayam (chicken meatball), Bakso Telur (egg meatball), etc.  The price is very cheap, its really worthed with the delicious meals.

However, the place isn't really big, and no Air Conditioning available there. So, on busy hour it is better to take away the food, or you should take a queue before enjoying your meals
review 2: Great bakso and the down to earth vibe and affordably priced, their prasmanan selection is great starting from steamed to fried wontons, stuffed tofu, noodles, sliced cabbage and greens. I tried the bakso stuffed squid it was too much for me but it‚Äôs really nice, my partner tried the iga bakso it was good although the iga was a bit hard to chew, the store itself is tiny and super hot, but the Indonesian do mind it. It was on the sidewalk parking for motorcycles and roadside for car.

review 4: I like the meatball, it's chewy and there are more than varieties you can choose and the broth tastes good too.
review 5: i'm in love with the bakso beranak. would like to comeback here next time and try another menu üëç
